article.headline: Carter surpasses 40 points for first time in a year

images.name: Carter Vince 030308 inline
images.caption: The Hawks couldn't find any answers for Vince Carter.

article.linkText: Raptors' Carter hits big the 4-0 for first time in a year
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- For the first time in a year, Vince Carter reached the 40-point plateau. Carter scored a season-high 43 points, the 11th 40-point game of his career, as the Toronto Raptors defeated the Atlanta Hawks 107-98 Saturday night. Carter finished 16-of-24 from the field, including 5-of-8 on 3-pointers, to set a Philips Arena scoring record for an opponent. It was his first 40-point game since a 43-point outing at Houston on March 5, 2002. His career high is 51 against Phoenix on Jan. 27, 2000. "This was not my best game,'' Carter said. "Just because I scored the most points doesn't make it my best game. I played to be effective, not to see how many points I could score. When you win, it all comes together.'' The Raptors had lost three of five coming in, including a two-point defeat to Houston on Wednesday when Carter missed a layup with 10 seconds left. But he was locked in against the Hawks. "It's a feeling that you get from seeing a guy -- when he works and plays and everything -- he was outstanding,'' said Raptors head coach Lenny Wilkens. "He went to the hoop, got the in-between shots, the outside shots, rebounded, defended and that was great for me.'' Voshon Lenard added 23 for Toronto, while Antonio Davis added 13 and Alvin Williams 10. Glenn Robinson led Atlanta with 29, while Shareef Abdur-Rahim scored 22 and Theo Ratliff had a season-high 20. Carter was electrifying in the first half, scoring 26 points on 10-of-15 shooting, nearly eight points over his season average and one shy of his season high. Trailing 28-25, Carter opened the second quarter with a short jumper followed by three successive 3-pointers to put the Raptors up 36-33. "I was feeling good,'' Carter said. "The first one felt pretty good. When I hit the second one, I decided just to try the third.'' Toronto's lead never exceeded five in the third quarter despite another strong series from Carter as he scored 11 of 13 Toronto points. It wasn't until his final scoring spurt in the fourth that Toronto was able pull away. There were four lead changes early in the fourth, the last coming on a pair of free throws by Davis that put Toronto up 87-86. Powered by Carter, the Raptors outscored Atlanta 20-12 the rest of the way. Nursing a three-point lead with four minutes left, Carter skied for an alley-oop dunk that also drew a foul. He missed the free throw, but the ball scooted back into his hands and he hit a short jumper to put Toronto up 98-91. He added two free throws to give him 43 before heading to the bench with just over a minute left. Aided by Family Night and a postgame concert by gospel/R&B group Mary Mary, low-drawing Atlanta recorded its first sellout crowd of the season (19,445) The Hawks, opening a four-game homestand, were looking to win their third straight after consecutive victories over league doormats Denver and Cleveland. But going 1-for-10 from 3-point range (10 percent) and 19-of-27 (70.4 percent) from the line doomed the Hawks. Atlanta point guard Jason Terry, who had been averaging over 20 points in his previous four games, was held to eight points on 4-of-15 shooting. "I thought the shots (Toronto) made were tougher than the shots we missed,'' Hawks coach Terry Stotts said. "You've got to give them credit when they make tough shots, but I was more disappointed with giving them some of the easy ones.'' If there was a bright spot for Atlanta, it was the performance of Ratliff. Bothered by a hip injury from virtually the day he was acquired from Philadelphia late in the 2000-01 season, Ratliff finally is starting to show some of his previous All-Star form. "Theo's been playing terrific,'' Stotts said. "He's offensive-minded. He had good looks. He played with confidence. We rely so much on him at the defensive end that when he gives us offense, we have to take advantage of it.''

Game notes
Atlanta is 7-2 in front of crowds over 15,000. ... The Hawks are 19-11 all-time against Toronto, including 10-6 in Atlanta, but have lost eight of their last nine against the Raptors. ... Shareef Abdur-Rahim had four assists to give him 1,501 for his career. ... When playing on consecutive nights, Toronto is 5-6 in the first game and 0-10 in the second. They play host to Memphis on Sunday.
